CM_ SG_ 128 ESCLDataControl "ESCL Communication.

Byte 1 Definition > 01=LockRequest, 03=Response, 04=Request final status

If Byte 1 = 0x01,

Byte 2 Definition > 0x01 = Unlock, 0x02 = Lock
Byte 3-8 > empty

If Byte 1 = 0x03

Bytes 2 - 5 Definition > Challenge Response
Bytes 6 - 8 Definition > empty 


If Byte 1 = 0x04

Byte 2 = 0x01
Bytes 3-8 = Empty
The MSB of the signal must be written to the COM layer first (with an offset of zero in wr_bytes() ) and therefore transmitted on the bus first.
Similarly, subscribing modules will receive the MSB of the signal when they call rd_bytes(0).

E.g. wr_bytes(0) = published_signal_MSB;

Subscribed_Signal_MSB = rd_bytes(0);

";
CM_ SG_ 130 ESCLDataTargetV2 "This is an updated version of the ESCLDataTarget message. The modifications will be indicated on the relevant lines below:

Communication with the BCM. 

Byte 1 Definition > 0x00=SystemStatus, 0x02=Challenge

If Byte 1 = żSystem statusż (0x00) then:

Byte 2 (ESCL locking Status) Definition:

0x55 = ESCL Unlocked (*/modified from originalESCLDataTarget)
0xAA = ESCL Locked (*/modified from originalESCLDataTarget)
0xFF = ESCL Invalid position (*/modified from originalESCLDataTarget)

Byte 3 (ESCL Unit Status) Definition:

0x55 = Unit Ok (*/modified from originalESCLDataTarget)
0xAA = Unit in fault state (*/modified from originalESCLDataTarget)
0x03 = Initial lock status mismatch
0x04 = Error detected on initialisation
0x05 = RAM error check failed
0x06 = Motor timed out
0x07 = Awating VIP Frame
0x80 = Inhibited ż Not in programmed
0x81  = cheallenge response error
0x82 = Unauthorised Lock request
0x83 = Inhibited ż Not authorised 
0xC3 = lock/unlock in progress (*/modified from origin";
CM_ SG_ 1360 NMmessageFTCM "Network Management Signal. This signal contains Network Management Data. This data includes the DA (Destination Address), CF (Control Field) and up to 6 data bytes of user defined data (currently not used by Jaguar). The signal name is made up of the following components:

NM represents 'Network Management'
5 represents the 0x5 part of the transporting CANID.	
02 represents the SA part of the transporting CANID.
LS indicates that this Signal is for LS-CAN Network Management.

The MSB of the signal must be written to the COM layer first (with an offset of zero in wr_bytes() ) and therefore transmitted on the bus first.
Similarly, subscribing modules will receive the MSB of the signal when they call rd_bytes(0).

E.g. wr_bytes(0) = published_signal_MSB;

Subscribed_Signal_MSB = rd_bytes(0);

CAN ID:
X150/X250 - 0x502
GMRDB - 0x550

";
CM_ SG_ 366 FTCM_Command "Commands to control internal motor of FTCMB ECU. Used to activate open and close movement, stop movement and activate initialization/deinitialization

Logical Value	0	 	 	Stop
Logical Value	1	 	 	DirectPosition
Logical Value	2	 	 	DirectDriveOpen
Logical Value	3	 	 	DirectDriveClose
Logical Value	4	 	 	SetNormalisation
Logical Value	5	 	 	DiscardNormalisation
Logical Value	6	 	 	ResetErrorFlags
Logical Value	7	 	 	Reserved
";
CM_ SG_ 366 FTCM_Command_Count "Incremented to signalize changed command. Used to trigger action if same command is sent twice

